\section*{Problem Statement}

A solid sphere, a hollow sphere, a solid disk, and a hoop with the same mass and radius are spinning freely about a diameter with the same angular speed on a table. For which object will maximum work have to be done to stop it?

\section*{Solution}

To determine which object requires the maximum work to stop, we need to consider the rotational kinetic energy of each object. The rotational kinetic energy \( K \) is given by:

\[
K = \frac{1}{2} I \omega^2
\]

where \( I \) is the moment of inertia and \( \omega \) is the angular speed.

The moments of inertia for the objects are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Solid sphere:} \( I = \frac{2}{5} m r^2 \)
    \item \textbf{Hollow sphere:} \( I = \frac{2}{3} m r^2 \)
    \item \textbf{Solid disk:} \( I = \frac{1}{2} m r^2 \)
    \item \textbf{Hoop:} \( I = m r^2 \)
\end{itemize}

Given that all objects have the same mass \( m \), radius \( r \), and angular speed \( \omega \), we can calculate the rotational kinetic energy for each:

\begin{align*}
K_{\text{solid sphere}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{2}{5} m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{5} m r^2 \omega^2 \\
K_{\text{hollow sphere}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{2}{3} m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{3} m r^2 \omega^2 \\
K_{\text{solid disk}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{1}{2} m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{4} m r^2 \omega^2 \\
K_{\text{hoop}} &= \frac{1}{2} \left(m r^2\right) \omega^2 = \frac{1}{2} m r^2 \omega^2
\end{align*}

The work done to stop each object is equal to its rotational kinetic energy. Therefore, the object with the maximum rotational kinetic energy will require the maximum work to stop.

Comparing the kinetic energies:
\[
K_{\text{hoop}} > K_{\text{hollow sphere}} > K_{\text{solid disk}} > K_{\text{solid sphere}}
\]

Thus, the hoop requires the maximum work to stop.

